[[File:Waguri Shrine Hachimangu Origin Record.jpg|thumb|250px|Origin record]]

'''Waguri Shrine''' (わぐりじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Shimamura (Ichinomiya City)|Q128848556|WD=Q128848556|lt=Shimamura|1=Shimamura}}, {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya City|Q270810|WD=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. Its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was Prefectural Shrine. The official name is “Waguri Shrine Hachimangū.” This is because it once bore the name Hachimangū. However, it is more commonly called Waguri Shrine.

It is the “Waguri Shrine” of {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q1032507|WD=Q1032507|1=Haguri District}}, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}.

=== Overview ===
The founding date is said to be during the {{ill|lt=Hakuhō period|Q11580612|WD=Q11580612|1=Hakuhō}}, when a local powerful figure of this region, Haguri no Omi Hitomaro, established the shrine to enshrine his ancestor (Ame-oshitara-hiko no Mikoto).

During the {{ill|lt=Tenbun era|Q1192853|WD=Q1192853|1=Tenbun}}, a Buddhist statue ({{ill|lt=Hachiman deity|Q261637|WD=Q261637|1=Hachiman}}) was jointly enshrined, and in {{ill|lt=1605|Q6741|WD=Q6741|1=1605}} (Keichō 10), the domain lord Kanematsu Masakichi (a retainer of {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Yoshinao|Q1136186|WD=Q1136186|1=Tokugawa Yoshinao}} of the {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|WD=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}}) formally enshrined Hachimangū, and the shrine was renamed Hachimangū.

In {{ill|lt=1869|Q7720|WD=Q7720|1=1869}} (Meiji 2), it was renamed back to Waguri Shrine and became a village shrine, but in {{ill|lt=1880|Q7806|WD=Q7806|1=1880}} (Meiji 13) it was again renamed Waguri Shrine Hachimangū.

In {{ill|lt=1935|Q18658|WD=Q18658|1=1935}} (Shōwa 10), it became a Prefectural Shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Ame-tarashihiko-kunioshi-hito no Mikoto|Q11443593|WD=Q11443593|lt=Ame-oshitara-hiko no Mikoto|1=Prince Ametarashihiko}}
*: A prince of {{ill|lt=Emperor Kōshō|Q312841|WD=Q312841|1=Emperor Kōshō}}. It is said that when Emperor Kōshō stayed in this area, he took as consort {{ill|lt=Yotsugi Tarashi-hime|Q10869205|WD=Q10869205|1=Yosotarashi-hime}}, the daughter of {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Oshin-O no Mikoto|Q97613650|WD=Q97613650|lt=Okitsu Yoae no Kimi|1=Amaoshio no mikoto}}, a local powerful figure. Their child was Ame-oshitara-hiko.
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}

=== Festivals ===
* Chigo Festival (May 5)
* Annual Festival (October 20)

=== Auxiliary shrines ===
* Kawashima Tenjin Shrine – One of the candidate sites (ronsha) for '''Kawashima Shrine''' of {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q1032507|WD=Q1032507|1=Haguri District}}, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.
* Kotohira Shrine
* Heiwa Shrine

=== Cultural properties ===
=== Designated cultural properties of Ichinomiya City ===
* Colored portrait on paper of Kanematsu Masakichi
* Three donated swords

=== Transportation ===
* Get off at the {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Bus|Q6810397|WD=Q6810397|1=Meitetsu Bus}} “Waguri Shrine-mae” bus stop; the shrine is just a short walk away.
** From {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station|Q2856589|WD=Q2856589|1=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagoya Main Line|Q1137838|WD=Q1137838|1=Meitetsu Nagoya Main Line}} or {{ill|lt=Bisai Line|Q901005|WD=Q901005|1=Meitetsu Bisai Line}}, or from {{ill|lt=Owari-Ichinomiya Station|Q871495|WD=Q871495|1=Owari-Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō Main Line (Nagoya area)|Q11235139|WD=Q11235139|1=Tōkaidō Line (JR Central)}} of {{ill|lt=Central Japan Railway Company|Q513679|WD=Q513679|1=Central Japan Railway Company}}, take a bus bound for “Kawashima” from platform 3 of the Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station Bus Terminal.

